Question: NullPointerExcetption with AppCompat and ActionBar: :The Activity I have crashes everytime with this error. If I add any code related to getSupportActionBar() it crashes within that. Otherwise it crashes out of thatpublic class DishTag extends ActionBarActivity  implements OnClickListener{ //....    @Override    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {       setContentView(R.layout.dish_tag);       super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);       context=this;       //literally all the code I have       ActionBar a=getSupportActionBar();       a.setTitle("SD");     }}To be noted and I don't know if this makes any difference but I am using a ViewPager on the page.The error is 11-30 22:06:38.212: E/AndroidRuntime(27315): Caused by:java.lang.NullPointerExceptionAttempt  to invoke virtual method 'java.lang.Class java.lang.Object.getClass()' on anull object reference
Please using this api: Activity.setContentView.
Answer: <<<api>>>: setContentView()
<<<code>>>: setContentView(R.layout.dish_tag);
<<<explanation>>>: This method sets the layout for the activity's window. You must call this method before adding content to your activity layout.

A: The NullPointerException is thrown when you try to call a method or access a field of a null object. In your case, it seems like you're trying to call getSupportActionBar() before calling super.onCreate(savedInstanceState).
The super.onCreate(savedInstanceState) call must be the first line in your onCreate() method. It sets up the basic activity stuff, including the ActionBar. If you call getSupportActionBar() before this, it will return null because the ActionBar hasn't been set up yet, and you'll get a NullPointerException when you try to call methods on it.
So, move super.onCreate(savedInstanceState) to the top of your onCreate() method:
@Override
protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    setContentView(R.layout.dish_tag);
    context=this;
    ActionBar a=getSupportActionBar();
    a.setTitle("SD");
    //...
}


A: You should call super.onCreate(savedInstanceState) before setContentView(R.layout.dish_tag);.
The super.onCreate(savedInstanceState) is where the ActionBar is set up.
So, your code should look like this:
@Override
protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    setContentView(R.layout.dish_tag);
    context=this;
    ActionBar a=getSupportActionBar();
    a.setTitle("SD");
}


